I have a new vehicle in the buildings build queue. Unfortunately, AI can't handle this.
I sort of fixed this in my mod but unfortunately, I'm not modding on bleed branch.
I'll just put the changes in patch form here.

New dictionary entry for YAML file "CoreDefinitions" is introduced. In the list, you list structures as keys and their respective core units as value so that AI will know which core to build when it intends a structure.
Also, the modder needs to list the core units in YAML's mcv list so that AI will attempt to deploy the cores.
```patch
--------------------- OpenRA.Mods.Common/AI/BaseBuilder.cs ---------------------
index 4f4ac164f..a58015df8 100644
@@ -292,7 +292,15 @@ ActorInfo ChooseBuildingToBuild(ProductionQueue queue)
 
 				// Can we build this structure?
 				if (!buildableThings.Any(b => b.Name == name))
-					continue;
+				{
+					// Well, check one more time. Check if it is defined in the core and buildable.
+					if (!ai.Info.CoreDefinitions.ContainsKey(name))
+						// Not even indirectly buildable with a "core".
+						continue;
+					if (!buildableThings.Any(b => b.Name == ai.Info.CoreDefinitions[name]))
+						// Indirectly buildable, but that core is not currently buildable.
+						continue;
+				}
 
 				// Do we want to build this structure?
 				var count = playerBuildings.Count(a => a.Info.Name == name);
@@ -328,7 +336,12 @@ ActorInfo ChooseBuildingToBuild(ProductionQueue queue)
 				// Lets build this
 				HackyAI.BotDebug("{0} decided to build {1}: Desired is {2} ({3} / {4}); current is {5} / {4}",
 					queue.Actor.Owner, name, frac.Value, frac.Value * playerBuildings.Length, playerBuildings.Length, count);
-				return actor;
+
+				// If a core actor, return the core instead.
+				if (ai.Info.CoreDefinitions.ContainsKey(name))
+					return world.Map.Rules.Actors[ai.Info.CoreDefinitions[name]];
+				else
+					return actor;
 			}
 
 			// Too spammy to keep enabled all the time, but very useful when debugging specific issues.

----------------------- OpenRA.Mods.Common/AI/HackyAI.cs -----------------------
index 443a887fb..8e2d905bc 100644
@@ -182,6 +182,8 @@ public class BuildingCategories
 		[FieldLoader.LoadUsing("LoadBuildingCategories", true)]
 		public readonly BuildingCategories BuildingCommonNames;
 
+		public readonly Dictionary<string, string> CoreDefinitions = null;
+
 		[Desc("What buildings should the AI have a maximum limit to build.")]
 		public readonly Dictionary<string, int> BuildingLimits = null;
```

@thm-projects nuked their https://scm.thm.de gitorious based infrastructure. Luckily I saved the code of their student project. It took me some time, but I found their converter scripts which converted the .ini file triggers to Lua prefabs. While these autogenerated .lua scripts still need manually polishing to become readable and maintainable, it is often better to start with something than from scratch.

https://gist.github.com/Mailaender/93e8041f2535cffaf2490c307bee4553#file-map-cs-L536 contains the code. This can't be integrated as is. It should be placed in an appropriate `UtilityCommands` module instead of the generic `Map` class they chose for their quick experiments.

See also https://scm.thm.de/redmine/projects/dtdj-ultj/wiki/Automatische_Generierung_von_Karten

This glitch is hard to pull off but here it is:
https://youtu.be/S4kc_d4OW4Y

* Normally when you order a full harvester to mine ore, it will return to the refinery.
* However, if you move the ore truck to where it unloads then order it to mine ore, it tries to reach the refinery but will not unload. (Being already there at the docking position causes the bug)

Not usually a problem but when you try to mod and try to make "Marv", which virtually "dock" by skipping drop-off location check, you get to skip the follwing SequenceActivities() call:

```csharp
DeliverResources.cs:Tick()

		if (self.Location !=  proc.Location + iao.DeliveryOffset)
				{
					var notify = self.TraitsImplementing<INotifyHarvesterAction>();
					foreach (var n in notify)
						n.MovingToRefinery(self, dest, this);

					return ActivityUtils.SequenceActivities(movement.MoveTo(dest, 0), this);
				}
```

If you get to skip this SequenceActivities(), you get the glitch shown as the video above.

Why are all the actions queued by iao.OnDock() not working if SequenceActivities is skipped?
What does SequenceActivities do? Not too sure as it has no comments in the code or documentation.

I am 99% sure it is SequenceActivities.
When I replace the if condition in the above code to something else (such ase actor's facing) and let the actor turn its facing with return ActivityUtils.SequenceActivities(new Turn(self, 0), this); you get no problem. (Unless the harvester is facing exactly 0 at the time of trying to dock)
